## The real gaps are in the data itself and in how we trained:

1. Training set is half the paper's size. ours_game_5000_trimmed actually contains 2,417 sequences despite the name. Paper
§C: "5000 training sequences" for synthetic TrackNet.
2. Training sequences are ~4× shorter than real TrackNet clips.
- Ours: seq_len mean 119, min 53, max 234
- Paper's synthetic TrackNet: length 64–822, ~3 strokes each (§C)
- Real TrackNet: we saw clips up to 870 frames in this eval (game7/Clip4)

This matters a lot: LSTM^f / LSTM^b are recurrent accumulators — they only learn to stay stable for horizons they were
exposed to. The model has literally never seen a 500-frame unroll. On long real clips the height accumulator drifts well
past what any training gradient taught it to correct.
3. Under-trained. 608 epochs logged, best ckpt at ep 540. Paper schedule is 1,400 epochs. We're at ~40% of the paper's
training budget, and the val NRMSE at ep 540 (0.024) is still wiggling — not converged.
4. Physics coverage is probably thinner. Paper's Unity/PhysX pipeline is tuned to "simulate a tennis game with two
players" (§4.1). Our max ball height is 3.67 m — that covers normal bounces but serves can reach 5 m (toss apex) and
smashes are ~3 m racket contact; worth checking the stroke mix.
5. Game 4 is the worst game (23.9 m error) and has the most extreme camera — fx=1100, height 3.82 m, elevation 9.9°.
That's at the corner of our training distribution (only a handful of our sequences have fx≈1100 and height<4 m and
elevation<10° simultaneously). Probably sparse coverage.

What would likely close most of the gap, in decreasing cost/benefit order:

- A. Resume training to 1,400 epochs. Cheap. Your train log already shows val NRMSE still drifting — you're leaving
accuracy on the table.
- B. Regenerate training data with paper-spec lengths (64–822 frames, ~3 strokes each). Medium cost but probably the
single biggest lever — long-horizon LSTM behaviour cannot be fixed by more epochs on short sequences.
- C. Increase training size to 5,000 sequences to match paper §C.
- D. Fill gaps at the low-focal / low-elevation corner of camera space where game4 sits.
- E. Everything else (noise aug, loss weights, etc.) — don't touch; we match the paper there.



The val_pred_vs_gt.png panel confirms it qualitatively — predicted (blue) and GT (red) trajectories overlay almost
perfectly in top-down and side views, across 6 sampled sequences.

So the model is correct — better than the paper on synthetic, in fact (2.4% NRMSE vs 9%). The training loss, the held-out
val NRMSE, and the visual overlay all agree.

