Summary: a ~10–17× gap on the headline landing metric, and essentially no usable bounce F1. Paper achieves 87.2% avg T.acc
and 0.81 F1 with a similar architecture trained similarly; we're at 3% and 0.01.

Interpretation — most of the 11 m error is geometry, not 11 m of 3D error. Reprojection is fine (5 px median), so the 3D
(x,y,z) is consistent with the 2D input — but the predicted y is ~1.5 m above ground at GT bounces, and for a broadcast
camera at ~7.85 m height and ~44 m distance, that 1.5 m height bias projects to ~1/tan(10°) ≈ 5–8 m of x-z displacement.
That matches our 6.2 m median landing error almost exactly. The numbers are geometrically self-consistent: one root cause
= height head not going to zero at ground contact on real data.

Per-game landing means range 7.6 – 23.9 m — game4 (23.9 m) is a strong outlier, worth inspecting the calibration vis. All
other games cluster around 7–13 m.

Bottom line: yes, this is a real sim-to-real gap, and it is much larger than the paper reports. Two realistic causes:

1. The v2 checkpoint is at epoch 540 of a 1400-epoch schedule — undertrained.
2. The v2 training data may not match the paper's synthetic TrackNet distribution (camera angles, stroke variety), so no
amount of training closes it.

