## Try this fix

This is a **smoking gun**. Here's the distribution mismatch:

| Feature   | Synthetic (training)               | Real TrackNet                      |
| --------- | ---------------------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| **p_g.z** | **[2.25, 47.74]**, always positive | **[-16.67, 69.36]**, ~30% negative |
| **p_v.y** | **[1.97, 7.71]**, always positive  | **[-9.04, 4.68]**, ~30% negative   |
| p_g.z < 0 | **0%**                             | **~30%**                           |
| p_v.y < 0 | **0%**                             | **~30%**                           |

The problem is exactly what you suspected. Here's the geometry:

**z=0 is at the net.** In the real TrackNet world coordinate system (from PnP with court keypoints), the baselines sit at z=±11.885m. When the ball is on the **camera side** of the net (z < 0), the ray from the camera through the ball must be extended **past the ball and through the net plane** to reach z=0. This produces a **negative p_v.y** — the vertical-plane intersection is *below ground*.

Our synthetic training data applied a `z_shift` of +18.3m, pushing **all** ball positions to z > 1.0. The model has **never seen negative p_v.y** or negative p_g.z. Then at inference on real data, ~30% of frames have these values.

This is catastrophic for `lift_to_3d`:
```
t = h / p_v.y
```
If p_v.y is negative but h is positive (ball above ground), then t < 0, which produces:
- `z = p_g.z * (1 - t)` — z gets pushed in the wrong direction
- `x = p_g.x + t * (p_v.x - p_g.x)` — x also inverted

The refinement LSTM can't recover from this because the initial `r_t` is geometrically flipped. This alone could explain the 11m landing error.

**The fix options:**
1. **Match the paper**: set z=0 at the net in both training AND inference (don't shift synthetic z), so the model learns to handle negative-z balls
2. **Shift real data too**: at inference time, translate the world coordinate system so all z > 0 (same convention as training) — this is easier but means redefining the extrinsic matrix per-clip

Option 2 is the quick fix. Want me to implement it?


